      {
        "id": 2084257,
        "name": "e chin",
        "username": "e_chin",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/e_chin/{size}/1388_2.png",
        "created_at": "2016-12-23T01:54:38.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>So I\u2019ve just found out that viognier isn\u2019t the only variety that is blended with syrah.  Marsanne and roussane can also be blended.  My question, since I am unfamiliar with these wines and in general N Rhone, why and what do these grape variety bring to the table?  I have read viognier is blended for aromatics, but have no idea about the others.  Also is there any discernable difference?</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 11,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-02T20:53:48.227Z",
        "reply_count": 0,
        "reply_to_post_number": null,
        "quote_count": 0,
        "incoming_link_count": 2,
        "reads": 0,
        "readers_count": 0,
        "score": 10.0,
        "yours": false,
        "topic_id": 128159,
        "topic_slug": "n-rhone-blending-question",
        "display_username": "e chin",
        "primary_group_name": "Grand_Cru_Cru",
