        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/g/8baadc/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2016-12-23T10:36:22.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"e chin\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n e chin:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>So I\u2019ve just found out that viognier isn\u2019t the only variety that is blended with syrah.  Marsanne and roussane can also be blended.  My question, since I am unfamiliar with these wines and in general N Rhone, why and what do these grape variety bring to the table?  I have read viognier is blended for aromatics, but have no idea about the others.  Also is there any discernable difference?</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Viognier is allowed only in C\u00f4te-R\u00f4tie (up to 20%), while Marsanne and Roussanne may be added to red Hermitage (max.15%), to Crozes-Hermitage and St.Joseph (10%) - but not to Cornas (where no white grapes are legal at all).</p>\n<p>The reason might on one hand be a pragmatic one \u2026 historically there were always some Marsanne and Roussanne vines grown between the Syrah, and it simply would be too complicated to sort them out, and on the other hand the white grapes soften the strong Hermitage and  makes it earlier accessable (and also more fragrant).</p>\n<p>To my knowledge less than a handful of producers have white grapes in their red Hermitage nowadays.</p>",
        "post_number": 10,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 11,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-02T20:53:57.555Z",
